About
Travellers Choice Best of the Best
2025
A triumph of ancient engineering. A resting place for kings and artists. A temple to the Gods. No wonder the Pantheon remains the beating heart of Romes historic center. Originally built around 27 BCE, this massive dome-topped monument was turned into a church in the seventh century and now draws millions of visitors each year. Before you step inside, take a (free) stroll around the outside of the Pantheon to see its curved exteriors. Then spring for a ticket to see the grand interiors. Its ornate geometry starts at the floor, basically a giant marble-and-granite checkerboard. Encircling that are columns and ornamental niches. And then theres the showstopper: that domed ceiling with an opening at the top (the oculus), that lets in natural light and acts like a sundial throughout the day. Its no wonder artists like Raphael asked to be buried hereits not a bad place to spend eternity.
Duration: 1-2 hours

Must-see highlights

  • Rotunda
    With marble floors and towering columns, this main room was built to impress.
  • Dome
    Nearly 2,000 years old, the Pantheon still has the worlds largest unsupported dome.
  • Oculus
    The so-called eye of the Pantheon, the opening at the top of the dome, is the only source of natural light.
  • Inscription
    At the entrance, youll see the names of the people behind the Pantheons construction and rebuilding.
  • Raphael's Tomb
    The Renaissance painter Raphael is buried under the Madonna del Sasso statue.
Things to know
  • You can book an advanced timed-entry ticket online. Guided tours are great deep-dives into the Pantheons rich history.
  • Opening hours are 9 a.m. to 7 p.m.; the last entry is 30 minutes before closing.
  • As with most popular sights in Rome, the best way to avoid the crowds is to come either within an hour or so of opening or in the evening.
  • If you can brave the crowds, theres an upside to visiting in the middle of the day: Thats when the most light filters from the oculus down into the rotunda.
  • If you happen to be here during a singing performance, consider yourself extra luckythe acoustics are heavenly.
  • On a budget? Its free to walk around the curved exterior and admire the dome from the outside.
  • The Pantheon is about a 10-minute walk to other sights like Piazza Navona, the Trevi Fountain, and the Temple of Hadrian.
Dedicated to the seven planetary divinities and featuring an interior of gorgeous marble, the Pantheon is one of the most impressive monuments of Augustan Rome.

The area
Address
Neighbourhood: Centro
Centro neighborhood in Rome, with its historical allure, beckons to the culturally curious. The neighborhood is home to the iconic Pantheon, a testament to Rome's ancient grandeur, and the picturesque Piazza Navona, a lively square filled with Baroque masterpieces. The narrow cobblestone streets are lined with an array of trattorias offering traditional Roman dishes, charming gelaterias, and artisan boutiques. With easy access to multiple bus lines and the Metro, Centro makes traversing the Eternal City a breeze. A stay in Centro offers an authentic immersion into Rome's rich tapestry of history, art, and gastronomy.
